{When asking ourselves what to play against the Sicilian Defence, we find
ourselves before a wide range of different approaches. The most usual is to
choose an open Sicilian with a sharp fight. This requires a lot of study time.
Once done, it again requires resources to stay updated on new games of each
variation. This is perfectly feasible for a professional player, but an
amateur may find it to take up too much time that would be better spent on
other aspects of the game. The Alapin Variation is a different, more economic
approach. It has a reputation of being peaceful and for players without great
ambition, but I consider this an error of judgment. The move 2.c3 is a choice
for the pragmatic player looking to fight for victory while saving resources.
Different types of positions can be reached, from high complexity to endgames
with a slight advantage. Many typical schemes, for example isolated pawn
positions, where the white player can demonstrate his greater familiarity with
them. From the other angle, it is often annoying for the average Sicilian
player to face structures that are rare in his practice. And as nowadays even
on the highest level players often stay away from mainline theory to avoid
preparation, it has been put into practice by Anand, Kramnik, Aronian,
Vachier-Lagrave, Ponomariov, and Adams, among others. There is also a group of
strong grandmasters who have played it regularly for many years, like Tiviakov,
Rozentalis, and Sveshnikov. For all these reasons, I recommend adding the
Alapin to your repertoire and wish you many victories with it.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3
d5 {In this first database we are going to concentrate on this move.} ({
The minor lines like} 2... b6 {2...Qa5; 2...e5; 2...a6; will be presented in
Chapter I.}) (2... d6 {A rare move, which can transpose to other openings, is
studied in Chapter II.}) (2... g6 {A popular line that is analysed in Chapter
III.}) 3. exd5 Qxd5 (3... Nf6 {A rare and dubious move-order by the second
player. It will be analysed in Chapter IV.}) 4. d4 Nf6 (4... g6 {This position
can also appear after 2...g6. It will be analysed in Chapter VI.}) (4... e5 {
An aggressive approach that does not cause problems for White. It is examined
in Chapter V.}) (4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Bf5 {An independent line that is gaining in
popularity. It is the subject of Chapter XII.} (5... Bg4 {This rapid bishop
development is analysed in Chapter VII.}) (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 e5 (6... Bg4 {
Chapter VIII.}) 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 e4 {This old line is the
subject of Chapter IX.}) (5... Nf6 6. dxc5 Qxc5 {can be found in Chapter XI.} (
6... Qxd1+ {Entering a very sharp middlegame without queens. This is analysed
in Chapter X.}))) 5. Nf3 e6 (5... Bg4 6. dxc5 Qxc5 {is the subject of Chapter
XIV.} (6... Qxd1+ {Entering the main version of this complex queenless
middlegame. It is the subject of Chapter XIII.})) 6. Na3 Nc6 {This move is
considered the mainline of this work. It is analysed in Chapter XX.} (6... Nbd7
{A rare way of developing that is the subject of Chapter XV.}) (6... cxd4 {
The direct exchange of pawns is analysed in Chapter XVI.}) (6... a6 {, taking
immediate control of the b5-square, is the subject of Chapter XVII.}) (6... Be7
{An elastic development move that is the subject of Chapter XVIII.}) (6... Qd8
{This queen retreat was one of the main lines in the initial stage of 6.Na3.
It is analysed in Chapter XIX.}) 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nb5 Qd8 (8... Qd7 {A
sophisticated square for the black queen. It gives rise to the modern line and
is the subject of Chapter XXI.}) 9. Nbxd4 *

