{[%evp 0,49,33,40,33,4,4,4,5,4,5,5,55,12,-4,10,22,13,8,10,10,8,1,1,1,4,16,12,
43,21,21,23,82,80,105,98,81,84,84,76,80,80,76,81,81,81,111,120,120,58,73,86]} 
1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. dxc5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {
Entering the main version of this peculiar middlegame without queens. Due to
the large number of games played and the large number of variations, it is
important to learn the thematic ideas. White's main plan is to hold the
c5-pawn with b4 and play on the queenside by advancing his majority. Useful
moves are Kc2-b3, Be3 (often defending the c5-pawn), Bb5 or Bc4-Nbd2. Of
course, the second player has a lot to say about this and will try to prevent
it. Despite the lack of queens, the game is usually highly complex. It is not
a minor detail that White's moves are usually easier or more natural than
those of his rival. This makes it an excellent choice to fight for victory and
I consider it a good recommendation for any Alapin player.} e5 ({In addition
to the main move, there are numerous alternatives seen in tournament practice.
} 7... Nc6 8. Be3 O-O-O+ (8... e5 9. h3 ({Attention deserves} 9. b4 $5 {
, not wasting time on the kingside.}) 9... Bxf3+ (9... Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Bb5
O-O-O+ 12. Nbd2 Nd5 (12... Ne4 $5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge4c5,Ge4c3,Rb2b4]} 13. Ke2
$1 Nxd2 (13... Bxc5 $4 14. Nxe4 $18 {Winning a piece.}) (13... Nxc5 $2 14. Bxc6
bxc6 15. Nxe5 $16 {[%cal Ge5g6,Ge5c6]}) 14. Nxd2 a6 15. Bc4 Na5 $1 {An
important disruptive move my Black who cannot allow the consolidation with 16.
b4.} 16. Bb3 {[%csl Rd3]} Bd3+ 17. Kf3 Nxb3 18. axb3 f6 19. Nc4 $14 {[%cal
Gh1d1] White has a slight advantage in a fighting endgame.}) 13. Ke2 {A
combative choice.} ({A different characteristic position appears after} 13.
