position very similar to that of Chapter XI. The only difference is that Black
has developed his bishop on g4 instead of his knight on c6. This slight change
allows for the possibility of developing the knight from b8 to d7 more solidly.
} 7. Na3 a6 {Useful move, but as a strong Grandmaster said once (if I am not
mistaken, it was Polugaevsky), the move a7-a6 is always a loss of tempo in the
opening. Which means that Black must be very careful after it and try to
develop his pieces quickly. With his next few moves, White seizes the
initiative.} (7... e6 8. Qa4+ Nc6 (8... Nbd7 9. Be3 {White continues taking
advantage of the exposed situation of the black queen to win time.} Qc8 ({
