exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 {The main move.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3b5,Ga3c4,
Ga3c2] An elastic and attractive knight development. The main idea is to
answer 6...cxd4 with 7.Nb5, threatening a fork on c7 and retaking with the
knight on d4. If the second player does not capture directly, as is frequently
the case, the knight on a3 has different routes to enter play via b5, c4, or
c2. A great specialist of this idea, who used it very successfully, is the
Russian Grandmaster Sergei Tiviakov.} (6. Be3 {For many years this was the
main move, leading to isolated pawn positions.}) 6... Nbd7 {A rare move and
somewhat passive.} 7. Bc4 {White takes advantage of the premature
centralisation of the black queen.} ({Another possibility is} 7. Be2) 7... Qe4+
(7... Qd6 8. Nb5 Qb8 (8... Qc6 9. Bf4 {[%cal Gb5c7]} Qe4+ (9... Nd5 10. Bxd5
Qxb5 11. a4 Qa6 12. Be4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 $14) 10. Be3 Qc6 11. O-O {The first
player has won some time to develop with immediate threats.} a6 12. a4 $1 axb5
