12... bxc6 {This time the second player is in a better position than in the
previous examples. His king is in the centre and his pawn on e5 is already
well defended.} 13. Nbd2 $14 {White begins to mobilize his pieces on the
queenside.} Kf7 14. a3 {A move that is almost always very useful to strengthen
the phalanx of pawns on the queenside. The direct advance to a4 is rarely
possible; it usually requires some preparation.} (14. a4 $2 Be7 {[%cal Gh8b8,
Gb8b4]} 15. Ne4 Rhb8 16. Bd2 Rb7 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb7a7]} 17. Ng1 Bf5 18. f3
Rba7 $15 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Rc2b3,Gf5e6,Ge6b3] It is Black who presses.}) 14...
g5 15. Bb2 Be7 16. Rad1 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gd2c4]} Rhb8 (16... Bf5+ 17. Ne4 Nf8 18.
Nfd2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gd2b3] The knight on f3 was no longer pinned by the bishop
and did not cooperate with the rest of the pieces.} Ng6 {[%cal Gg6f4,Gg6h4]}
19. g3 Bg4 20. Rc1 Be6 {[%cal Ge6c4,Rd2c4] Avoiding the knight jump to c4, but
White can also activate it via b3.} 21. Nb3 a4 22. Na5 {[%cal Ga5c6,Ge4d6,
Ga5b7,Gb7d6]} Rxa5 23. bxa5 Ra8 24. c4 Bxc4 25. Bc3 {The position is complex.
Black has compensation for the sacrificed exchange, but the position of the
first player is preferable.}) 17. Ne4 Bf5 (17... Be6 $5) 18. Re3 ({I prefer to
immediately activate the f3-knight with} 18. Nfd2 Be6 19. Nf1 Bd5 20. f3 {
[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf1e3,Gg2g4] With the idea of strengthening the control of the
light squares after Ne3 and g4.} axb4 21. cxb4 {Given the aforementioned idea,
the second player has to react, otherwise he will find himself in a losing
position. A possible continuation is} Nxc5 $5 22. bxc5 Bb3+ 23. Kc1 Bxd1 24.
Rxd1 Rb5 25. Kc2 h5 (25... Bxc5 26. a4 $1 $16) 26. Nfd2 Bxc5 27. a4 $1 {
A nice resource.} Rxa4 28. Nc3 Rxb2+ 29. Kxb2 Rh4 30. Rh1 $16) 18... Bf8 $6 ({
Black should take advantage of the opportunity to activate his pieces with} 
18... axb4 19. cxb4 Nxc5 $5 20. bxc5 Bxc5 21. g4 Bg6 22. Rdd3 (22. Re2 Bxa3 {
With a balanced game.}) 22... Bxe3 23. Rxe3 h5 24. h3 hxg4 25. hxg4 Rh8 26.
Nfd2 Rh4 27. f3 Rh2 28. Bc1 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gd2c4] Due to the reduced number
of pawns, Black has a good chance to level the game.}) 19. Nfd2 $1 $16 {
[%cal Gd2c4,Gd2b3] Putting the remaining piece into play.} g4 20. Nc4 ({
Also possible is} 20. f3 $5 h5 21. Rd3 Kg6 22. Nf1 Rd8 23. Ne3 Be6 24. Nd6 $16)
20... Ke6 21. f3 gxf3 ({Another option is} 21... h5 22. Red3 axb4 23. cxb4 Ra7
24. Bc1 h4 25. Ne3 Bxe4 26. fxe4 $16 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge3f5,Ge3g4]}) 22. gxf3
axb4 23. cxb4 $16 Be7 (23... Ra4 {does not help either.} 24. Ncd6 Bg6 25. Ree1
Be7 26. f4 $1 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gf4f5]} Nxc5 27. f5+ Bxf5 28. Nxf5 Kxf5 29. Nxc5
Bxc5 30. bxc5 Rc4+ 31. Bc3 Rxc5 32. Rd6 $16) 24. Red3 Ra7 25. Bc1 Rg8 26. Kb3
Bxe4 (26... h5 27. Be3 Bxe4 28. fxe4 Rg4 {[%csl Re4]} 29. Nd6 Nb8 30. a4 {
The queenside pawns advance without opposition.} Rd7 31. b5 h4 32. b6 $16) 27.
fxe4 Bxc5 ({White is on the verge of victory. Below are two variations where
exchange sacrifices are used to continue the progress on the queenside.} 27...
h5 28. Rd6+ $1 Bxd6 29. Rxd6+ Ke7 30. Rxc6 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4,Gc5]} Nb8 31. Rb6 Nd7
32. Rd6 Rc7 33. Be3 Rg2 34. Rd2 $18) (27... Rg2 28. Rd6+ $1 Bxd6 29. Rxd6+ Ke7
30. Rxc6 Rxh2 31. b5 Rh1 32. b6 Ra6 33. Bd2 $18) 28. Na5 $6 ({The precise path
is} 28. Be3 $1 Bxe3 (28... Bd4 29. Bxd4 exd4 30. Rxd4 $18) 29. Rd6+ Ke7 30.
Nxe3 Rga8 31. a4 $18) 28... Rc7 29. Rc3 $2 {An error that could have cost the
