Nxe8 Kxe8 33. Rh7 {And White is better, as Black's king cannot participate
very much. He has to play very precisely though, because of the potential of
the black pawns on the kingside.}) 22... Be4 23. axb7+ Kxb7 24. Ba6+ Ka8 25.
Bc7 h4 26. b5 {White presses and forces his opponent to give up material.} Na5
27. Bxa5 Bxc5 28. Bxd8 Rxd8 29. Re1 h3 30. Ra2 f5 31. Rd2 {With an extra rook,
White's position is preferable. Still, it should be noted that the game is far
from being finished. Black has compensation with his mass of pawns on the
kingside.}) 21. axb7+ Rxb7 22. Ra6 $18 {White is winning.} Bd7 (22... Nb8 23.
Rxf6 Bd7 24. Na5 {[%cal Gc5c6,Ga5b7,Gh2b8,Gf1a6] The white pieces have too
many threats to be neutralized.} Rxb4+ 25. cxb4 Bg7 26. Be5 Re8 27. Bc3 Bxf6
28. Bxf6 Re2+ 29. Kc3 Nc6 30. Bxe2 fxe2 31. Nc4 $18) 23. Nb6+ $1 Rxb6 24. cxb6
(24. Rxb6 $1 {is even better.} Re8 25. Ba6+ Kd8 26. Rb7 $18) 24... Kb7 25. bxa7
Be7 (25... Ra8 26. Bc4 Rxa7 27. Rd1 $18) 26. Bc4 Be8 27. Rha1 Ka8 28. Rb6 Nxa7
29. Bd5+ 1-0

