14... c5 {We find a structure where the c-pawns are more advanced, offering
both players more central control.} 15. Qc2 ({A different setup is} 15. Qe2 Qb6
16. Bc3 Bd7 17. O-O (17. h4 e5 18. h5 O-O-O 19. O-O Bg4 20. Rfb1 $13 {[%cal
Ga2a3,Gb2b4] The position is unclear but White's plan is obvious and easy to
play.}) 17... O-O 18. Qd2 e5 19. Rad1 Bf5 20. Nh4 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Rad8 22. Nf5
Nxf5 23. Qxf5 Bb8 24. b3 $14) 15... f5 {An attractive and ambitious
continuation by the second player.} (15... Bb7 16. Be4 (16. O-O-O {leads to a
rather murky game.} Bxf3 17. gxf3 Kf7 18. f4 f5 $13) 16... Qb6 17. Bc3 Rd8 18.
O-O-O Bxe4 19. Qxe4 e5 20. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4g7,Gg4e6]} (20. g4 $5) 20... O-O 21.
Rd2 Bc7 22. Rhd1 $14) 16. Bc3 ({Probably more accurate is} 16. O-O-O Nc6 17.
Rhe1 O-O 18. Bc3 Rb8 19. Qe2 ({Also playable is} 19. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2d6,Gd2e3]}
Qc7 {[%cal Gd6f4]} 20. g3 Be7 21. Qe3 Bf6 22. Qxc5 Bxc3 23. bxc3 Rb7 24. Ne5
$14) 19... Qb6 20. Qe3 Be7 21. Bc2 Bf6 22. Rd6 (22. a3 Na5 23. Ne5 $14) 22...
Bxc3 23. Qxc3 Qc7 24. Rd2 Rd8 25. Rxd8+ Qxd8 26. Rd1 Qe7 27. Ba4 Bb7 28. Bxc6
Bxc6 29. Ne5 Qg5+ 30. Qd2 Qxd2+ 31. Rxd2 Bxg2 32. Rd7 {White has ample
compensation for the sacrificed pawn and good chances to play for a win.})
16... O-O 17. O-O-O Qc7 18. Rhe1 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Re6][%cal Ge1e5] White has
some pressure on the e-file and his pieces are well placed.} Nc6 ({A different
attempt is the reasonable} 18... Rb8 19. g3 Nc6 20. Qe2 Be7 21. Bc2 Bf6 22. Qe3
{[%cal Ge3c3]} Nb4 23. Bb1 Bxc3 24. Qxc3 Rb6 25. Qe3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge3c5,
Gf3e5,Ga2a3]} Qe7 26. Ne5 Ra6 27. a3 $14) 19. Qe2 a5 20. g3 ({More exact is} 
20. Kb1 a4 21. a3 Be7 22. Bc2 Bf6 23. Qe3 Bxc3 24. Qxc3 Bd7 25. Rd2 $16 {
[%csl Rc5,Ge5]}) 20... Be7 21. Bc2 (21. Qe3 a4 (21... Ra6 22. a3 a4 23. Bc2 Na5
24. Ne5 Nb3+ 25. Bxb3 axb3 26. h4 $16 {White controls the dark squares.}) 22.
a3 Bf6 23. Bc2 Nd4 24. Nxd4 cxd4 25. Bxd4 Qxc4 26. Bxf6 gxf6 27. Qd4 $14 {
The first player has an easy game and can increase his advantage.}) 21... Qb6 (
{Some variations to understand the dynamics of the position are:} 21... Nb4 22.
Bb1 Nc6 23. a3 Bf6 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Qe3 Ne7 26. Rg1 $5 {A surprising idea to
generate more weaknesses.} (26. g4 $5) 26... Ng6 27. g4 $36) (21... Bf6 22. Qe3
Nb4 23. Bb1 a4 24. a3 Nc6 25. Bc2 Bxc3 26. Qxc3 Ra5 27. Qe3 Qe7 28. h4 $16) 22.
Ba4 Nb4 23. b3 $1 {A precise move. While taking away squares from his own
light-squared bishop, White also nullifies Black's queenside counterplay.} Bf6
24. Be5 $16 {Black is in a passive position.} ({Even better is} 24. Ne5 $1 Ra6
(24... h6 25. a3 Na6 26. Rd2 Nb8 27. Red1 Kh7 28. f4 $16) 25. a3 Bxe5 26. Bxe5
Nc6 27. Bc3 Qb7 28. Bb5 Rb6 29. Kb2 $16) 24... Na6 25. Rd6 $18 {White enjoys a
great advantage.} Qb4 26. Bxf6 ({More accurate is} 26. Bb2 $1 Nb8 27. Ne5 Qb7
28. f4 Ra7 29. Red1 {With white domination all over the board.}) 26... gxf6 27.
Kb2 Nc7 28. a3 Qb8 29. Red1 Ra7 30. Rd8 Na8 31. Qe3 Raf7 32. Be8 Rc7 33. Qh6
