17. Bc4 Bd7 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. Rd3 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd3g3] A simple but
excellent manoeuvre that guarantees an advantage.} Bc8 (19... Kh7 20. Rg3 Be8
21. Qg4 Rg8 22. Bxh6 $1 f5 23. Qg5 {[%cal Gh6g7]} Bf8 24. Re1 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,
Gg1h2,Ge1e6] All white pieces are active. The immediate threat is 25.h3 or 25.
h4 and capturing the black pawn on e6.}) 20. Rg3 $1 {[%cal Gg3g7,Gf4h6]} Bd6
21. Qg4 $1 {Very precise sequence of moves by the Russian player.} g6 22. Bxh6
Bxg3 23. Qxg3 {[%cal Gh6f8]} Qc5 (23... Qd6 {does not solve his problems
either.} 24. Qh4 Qe5 25. Bxf8 Rxf8 26. Rd1 $16) 24. Bxf8 ({Another possibility
is} 24. Bb3 Rfe8 25. Bg5 Rd3 ({Trying to keep the exchange only makes the
problems worse.} 25... Rd7 26. Re1 Qf5 27. Qh4 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Re8]}) 26. Qxd3
Qxg5 27. Qd4 b6 28. h4 $16) 24... Kxf8 25. Bb3 $6 ({Much more precise is} 25.
Qf4 $1 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gf4d2]} Kg7 26. Bb3 b6 27. Re1 a5 28. h4 Bb7 29. Rd1
$16) 25... Kg7 $6 ({Black loses the opportunity to put up active resistance
with} 25... Rd2 $1 26. h4 Kg7 27. Qf4 Re2 28. h5 gxh5 (28... Qxh5 $4 29. Qc4
$18) 29. Qg3+ Kf8 30. Rd1 $14 {White is better, but Black has counterplay.})
26. Qf4 $1 {Controlling the square d2.} b6 27. Rd1 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 e5 (28... Qb5
29. Qd2 Ba6 30. h4 $16) 29. Qd2 {We arrive at an endgame with a clear extra
pawn for White. In a first stage, Tiviakov will gradually improve his position.
} Be6 30. a3 Bd5 31. Bc2 (31. h4 $5) 31... Qc4 32. Bd3 Qc6 33. Qg5 $1 {Forcing
the weakening of the black pawn on e5.} e4 (33... Qd6 34. Bf1 Be6 35. h4 $16)
34. Qe5+ Kh7 35. Be2 Bc4 36. Bd1 f5 $6 {This advance makes the task of the
first player easier.} (36... Be6 37. h4 $16) 37. Qd4 Bf7 38. g3 Qe6 39. b3 ({
It is more promising to fix the black pawns on the kingside with} 39. h4 $1 Qa2
40. Qd7 Kg8 41. Qd2 a6 42. h5 $1 {An effective break with the black queen on
the other side of the board.} Kh7 (42... gxh5 43. Be2 {[%csl Ra6,Rf5][%cal
Ge2a6,Gd2g5,Gg5f5]} b5 44. Qg5+ $18) 43. Be2 {White has increased his
advantage.}) 39... g5 40. Qd2 (40. h3 $5) 40... Qf6 41. Qd4 Qe7 (41... Kg7 42.
Kf1 f4 43. Ke2 Qxd4 44. cxd4 Kf6 45. Kd2 Be6 46. Bc2 Bd5 47. Kc3 $16) 42. b4 f4
({Another way to prolong the fight can be} 42... Qe6 43. Be2 g4 $5) 43. Bg4 $1
e3 $2 44. fxe3 ({More exact is} 44. gxf4 $1 gxf4 (44... e2 45. Qd3+ $18) 45.
Qxf4 exf2+ 46. Kxf2 $18) 44... fxe3 45. Kf1 b5 46. Ke1 Bc4 47. Qd7 Qxd7 48.
Bxd7 $18 {White is winning.} Kg6 49. Bg4 Kf6 50. Be2 Bd5 51. Bxb5 Bf3 52. h4
gxh4 53. gxh4 Ke5 54. Be2 Be4 55. h5 Kf4 56. c4 Ke5 57. c5 Kd4 58. h6 Ke5 59.
b5 1-0

