15... Nd5 16. Bg3 Rac8 17. Rfe1 Bf6 18. h4 $14 {The typical advance of the
white h-pawn is going to force a weakening of the enemy king.} Ne7 ({Other
Black alternatives of similar value are:} 18... g6 19. h5 Bg7 (19... Ba4 {
Seeking to disturb the coordination of the white pieces.} 20. Rd2 e5 21. Nf3
Nf4 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Bxf4 exf4 24. Qc4 Bc6 25. Qxf4 $14) 20. Bh4 Re8 21. Nf3
Ba4 22. Rd2 Bc6 23. Bg5 $14 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gf3e5]}) (18... Ba4 19. Rd2 Ne7 20. h5
Rd5 21. Bf4 Bxd4 22. cxd4 Qd8 23. Be4 Rd7 (23... Rxd4 $2 24. Rxd4 Qxd4 25. Be5
$16) 24. h6 $14 {White's position is much more attractive.}) 19. h5 Ba4 ({
Worth considering is} 19... Rc5 $5 {A useful defensive resource, bringing the
rook into play horizontally.} 20. Nb3 Rcc8 (20... Rd5 21. Rxd5 Nxd5 22. h6 Ne7
23. Be5 $14) 21. h6 Ng6 22. hxg7 $13) 20. b3 ({Another possibility is} 20. Rd2
Rd5 21. Bf4 (21. Qg4 $5) 21... Bxd4 22. cxd4 Qd8 23. Be4 Rd7 24. h6 $14 {
Reaching the position already seen after 18...Ba4.}) 20... Be8 21. Qe4 $14 g6
22. Bh4 $1 $36 {White enjoys the initiative thanks to his play on the kingside.
} Bxh4 $6 ({Somewhat better is} 22... Nd5 23. hxg6 hxg6 24. Bxf6 Nxf6 25. Qh4
$36 {[%cal Gg3h3]}) 23. Qxh4 Nf5 $6 {A second inaccuracy that will cost the
second player dearly.} (23... Rd7 {White already has an advantage as shown in
the following variations:} 24. Nf3 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Nf5 26. Bxf5 exf5 27. Re1 {
[%csl Re8][%cal Ge1e8]} f6 28. hxg6 Bxg6 29. Re3 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Rf5,Rf6,Rg6]})
(23... Qc5 24. Be4 g5 25. Qg4 h6 26. Bb1 Rd6 27. Qe4 f5 28. Qxb7 $16) 24. Bxf5
$1 exf5 25. hxg6 ({Even stronger is} 25. Nxf5 Rxd1 26. Ne7+ Kf8 27. Rxd1 Rc5
28. Nd5 Qd6 29. c4 $18 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Gh4d4,Gd4h8] In addition to the extra
pawn and a centralized knight, White still has play against the black king.})
25... hxg6 26. Rd3 Bd7 27. Re7 ({Tiviakov now makes a safe decision. He could
have won faster with} 27. Rh3 $18) 27... Kg7 28. Rxd7 Rxd7 29. Nxf5+ gxf5 30.
Rxd7 Rxc3 31. Rd8 Rc1+ 32. Kh2 Qc7+ (32... Qh6 $4 33. Rg8+ $18) 33. f4 f6 34.
